FordGoBike - Tripdata¶

DataSet Overview¶

This Dataset is from FordGoBike - tripdata where the data has around 16 Variables explaining the users behaviour in using the company service.¶

duration_sec
start_time
end_time
start_station_id
start_station_name
start_station_latitude
start_station_longitude
end_station_id
end_station_name
end_station_latitude
end_station_longitude
bike_id
user_type
Date_time_start
Date_time_end
dtype: object

This data has the informations not for the Whole year but we have the data for the Second part of the year (i.e) from the June 2017 to December 2017¶

Analysing the data¶

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

From the explaoration, it can be obeserved that the dataset has 20000+ bike rides that happen in 2019 in the San Francisco Bay Area. The dataset contained interesting features like:

trip duration: how long the trip took in seconds

start time/end time: start/end date/time for the bike rides.

stations: start/end station, name, geolocation (latitude/longitude)

rented bikes: bike id

Further exploration to enhance the features that I may find neccessary to perform interesting analysis rental time: hour of the day, weekday

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

My area of interest is to invetigate the actual duration of biking time.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

To me the following features may help to support my investigation into the feature (duration) I am interested in.

user_type

start_time - I'll extract dayofweek, hours for further investigation.

month - I'll extract month, hours for further investigation.

time_of_day - I'll extract month, hours for further investigation.

# compute the logarithm of price to make multivariate plotting easier
def log_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """ a function to compute log and power operations """
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)

new_df['log_duration_min'] = new_df['time_mins'].apply(log_trans)

Insight¶

  • And it is surprising because we noticed in the previous graphs that the Tuesday and Wednesday are the most preferred day for the user to pick the services from the company,but they tend to use the service for longer time in Saturday nad Sunday.

  • As we already know that the months October and September are the most preferred months for the users but every month they tend to use the services for longer times on Saturdays and Sundays.

    """ Quick hack for creating histograms with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    palette = kwargs.pop('color')
    bins_x_1 = 10 ** np.arange(0,3.2+0.1,0.1)
    ticks_1 = [0.1,0.3,1,3,10,30,100,300,1000]
    labels_1 = ['{}'.format(v) for v in ticks]
    plt.hist(x,bins = bins_x_1)
    plt.xscale('log')
    plt.xticks(ticks_1,labels_1);
